<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12008a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12008a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12008a"> 8(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ purist</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il n&apos;y a plus de <i>bon usage</i>. Je ne vous engage point &agrave; l&apos;aller chercher dans les salons; vous y entendriez que Mme X&hellip; est <i>partie dans le Midi</i>, o&ugrave; elle <i>s&apos;emb&ecirc;te</i>, que M. Z&hellip; <i>lui</i> a caus&eacute; et qu&apos;il se rappelle fort bien <i>de</i> ce qu&apos;elle lui a dit. A quelle autorit&eacute; nous fier, sinon &agrave; nos lectures et &agrave; un bon dictionnaire? De la sorte, nous encourrons peut-&ecirc;tre le reproche d&apos;&eacute;crire le fran&ccedil;ais comme une langue morte, que je consens qui est en partie justifi&eacute;; mais l&apos;&eacute;tat o&ugrave; l&apos;on voit notre langage ne permet point d&apos;&eacute;chapper cette critique; et j&apos;avoue que je suis peu troubl&eacute; des mots de &ldquo;<mark>puriste</mark>&rdquo; ou d&apos;&ldquo;archa&iuml;sant&rdquo; que nos litt&eacute;rateurs sans lettres ont accoutum&eacute; de jeter comme des insultes aux rares auteurs qui s&apos;efforcent encore d&apos;&eacute;crire &agrave; peu pr&egrave;s correctement. <br><font color="green">[There is no longer a good usage. I am not going to tell you to look for it in the salons; you will hear there that Madame X is <i>partie dans le Midi</i>, or that she <i>s&apos;emb&ecirc;te</i>, that Madame Z&hellip; <i>lui</i> has spoken and that he fondly remembers <i>de</i> that which she has said to him. Whose authority do we trust, if not that of our reading and a good dictionary? Maybe as a result we will be accused of writing a French that is a dead language, and I admit that this is in part justified; but the current state of our language does not allow us to escape that accusation; and I admit that I do not mind being called a &ldquo;purist&rdquo; or a &ldquo;archaizer&rdquo; or other terms used by our illiterate writers to insult the rare authors who still try to write more or less correctly.]</font> <font color="green">[VI.C.15.270(k)]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 110 [On how French is currently spoken]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>Madame est partie dans le midi o&ugrave; elle s&apos;emb&ecirc;te</i>: Madam has gone to the Midi where she is bored. </mm> </dd></dl>
